    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-09-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-09-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="218"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d218">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 493.11/389.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Counselor of the Department of
                            State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Memorandum.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-09-18">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">September</hi> 18, 1913</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The crisis of 1900 is not a precedent in this instance. That was a purely
                    anti-foreign movement, not resisted by the Government; the present crisis that
                    of a domestic revolution. Where governments send their military and naval forces
                    to foreign countries in case of domestic disturbances, it is not customary for
                    them to make the expense a charge against the foreign country.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. B. Moore</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
